As many of you already know, Oregon Governor Kate Brown announced today that schools will continue to be closed for the remainder of the year. With this in mind, the Oregon Department of Education has outlined a clear pathway for Seniors to graduate on time. Seniors and their parents will be contacted by Sutherlin High School staff before April 30th with the details of this pathway. All other students will be expected to participate in “Distance Learning for All” that begins on April 13th. Thank you for your patience and understanding.

This service will only be available to households that have existing Charter Spectrum cable running into their homes.

For more information or to order services call Charter Spectrum at 1 (833) 267-6094.

Charter Spectrum also offers a Spectrum Internet Assist program for qualifying customers. For more information please visit the following site.

Good afternoon. Here is some updated school closure information.

Schools are closed through March 31st.
Breakfast and lunch meals will be provided at no charge for children 18 and under during the school closure. These will be grab and go meals and will not be consumed on-site. Meals will be served Monday through Friday at West Intermediate School, Breakfast will be served 7:30 to 8:30am and lunch will be served 11:30am to 12:30pm.

The District prepared for students to receive instruction during this time, however, after receiving more direction from the Oregon Department of Education, no instruction will take place during the closure. All Staff will return on March 30th & 31st and students are set to return on Wednesday, April 1st.

Thank you for your patience and support.

post_text:
Sutherlin School District Bond Levy Q&A
How much would it cost if the proposed bond levy were to pass?

If passed, the current tax rate would change to an estimated $1.29 per $1,000 of assessed value.

As an example, a property owner inside the Sutherlin School District with an assessed value of $100,000 would pay a total of approximately $129 per year, or an additional $10.75 per month, if the levy passes. A property owner inside the Sutherlin School District with an assessed value of $200,000 would pay a total of approximately $258 per year, or an additional $21.50 per month. If the levy is not passed, the tax would not go into effect and the projects would not be completed.

Governor Kate Brown Announces Statewide School Closure for Students in Oregon from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31.

In consideration of staffing challenges and health concerns due to the public health threat of coronavirus, Governor Kate Brown today announced a statewide closure of Oregon K-12 schools from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31.

Schools are operating today March 13th. We will update students and parents as more details become available.

Sutherlin School District is committed to working with students, staff and our community as we manage this rapidly changing situation. Thank you for your support.

Sutherlin schools are open. With the rapidly changing conditions of Covid-19 we want to ensure staff and parents we are following guidelines from the Oregon Dept. of Education, and the Oregon Health Authority. We will keep you informed as we receive additional information.

post_text:
Sutherlin School District Bond Levy Q&A
What is a General Obligation Bond (G.O. Bond)?

G.O. Bonds are tax levies that, if passed by voters, would allow school districts, community colleges, cities, and counties to fund capital improvement projects that otherwise might not be completed with general fund dollars. G.O. Bonds decided in May or November elections are approved or failed on a majority vote. ‘Double majority’ approval is not necessary in Primary or General Elections in the state of Oregon.

post_text:
Sutherlin School District Bond Levy Q&A
What are the proposed projects?

If the levy passes, the projects identified by the Sutherlin School Board are:

Replace West Intermediate School with a new, two-story, academic building on district owned property on Umatilla Street; Complete repair and maintenance projects on buildings district-wide, including, but not limited to, roofing, paint, and siding; Construct secure entryways, with fencing and camera systems to increase safety for students and staff; Replace windows to improve energy efficiency; and, improve communications systems between buildings for safety.

If passed, the current tax rate would change to an estimated $1.29 per $1,000 of assessed value. If the levy is not passed, the tax would not go into effect and the projects would not be completed.

post_text:
Sutherlin School District Bond Levy Q&A
What dollar amount is proposed for the G.O. Bond?

If the measure passes, taxpayers would pay a total of $22 million over 30 years. The current proposal includes the recently awarded OSCIM (Oregon School Capital Improvement Matching Program) “matching” grant from the State of Oregon for $4 million. If the G.O. Bond is passed by voters, Sutherlin School District would receive the matching funds to assist with the proposed projects. If the levy does not pass, the grant would not be awarded to the district, the levy would not be assessed, and the projects would not happen.

Sutherlin School District Bond Levy Q&A
How much would it cost if the proposed bond levy were to pass?

If passed, the current tax rate would change to an estimated $1.29 per $1,000 of assessed value.

As an example, a property owner inside the Sutherlin School District with an assessed value of $100,000 would pay a total of approximately $129 per year, or an additional $10.75 per month, if the levy passes. A property owner inside the Sutherlin School District with an assessed value of $200,000 would pay a total of approximately $258 per year, or an additional $21.50 per month. If the levy is not passed, the tax would not go into effect and the projects would not be completed.

post_text:
Proposed G.O. BOND Q&A
Question 7: Why were these projects proposed? What about the Career Technical Education (CTE)/vocational program facilities?

Answer: The state of Oregon is helping school districts fund CTE program improvements through Measure 98, which was approved by voters in 2016. The Sutherlin School District is currently in the process of using Measure 98 funding to improve CTE programs. Those funds have allowed Sutherlin to build a new agricultural science building and purchase a modern dust collection systems for the wood shop. Because of Measure 98 funding, the Sutherlin School District can use bond levy revenue to address other projects.

Proposed G.O. BOND Q&A
Question 1: What is a General Obligation Bond (G.O. Bond)?

Answer: G.O. Bonds are loans that are broken into pieces and sold to investors. It is essentially an extra property tax levy.
• Levy rates can and will fluctuate over the life of an issue, depending on the actual growth rate in assessed value.
• Districts cannot guarantee a rate; actual rate paid will depend on assessed value in future.

post_text: Sutherlin School District is aware of a disruption that occurred today in the Therapeutic Learning Class located on the West Intermediate campus. The TLC is a transitional program serving students in kindergarten through sixth grade from around the county and is administered through the Douglas Education Service District and Compass Behavioral Health. The disruption was brought under control without incident. Police were called to the class, but no action was taken. The safety of all students on our campuses is our top priority. There is word of the incident circulating on social media and we appreciate the community’s concern. We would like to reassure parents and families that our students are safe and that this is being handled by Douglas ESD and Compass Behavioral Health.

Sutherlin FFA Chapter
April 15, 2019 at 6:40 PM ·

We are looking for help with our service project this week! Please share!

The Sutherlin FFA Chapter is partnering with our CTE-Woods program and Sleep in Heavenly Peace (SHP) to build bunk beds for families and kids in need this Friday! Our goal is to BUILD 100 BEDS in one day, and we know our members are up to the challenge!

Thanks to great supporters, we have all wood material donated and ready to go! WHAT WE NEED is mattresses and new bedding to go to these families!

HOW CAN YOU HELP?
1 - Pledge a dollar for every bed we build, up to 100 beds.
2 - Sponsor a mattress ($55) for someone
3 - Donate twin-sized, new bedding items (blankets/sheets/pillows - no used bedding please).

Please help us hustle this week and make a difference for so many people in our community! You can contact the school or message this Facebook page. Help us make a difference! And check back Friday to see how it went!

post_text: Due the significant weather event last week, Sutherlin Schools will be altering our calendar to add make up days. We are currently determining how, when and the amount of time that will need to be made up. As a district, we needed to assess damages to our facilities before developing a plan that will be released early next week after school board approval. Thank you for your patience as we determine how best to serve our students and community.

post_text:
Message from Sutherlin School District. The Sutherlin High School gymnasium is currently a work zone. The recent snow storm followed by subsequent snow melt created leaks inside the gymnasium. Servpro, Pierce Restoration, All Aspects, along with other subcontractors are currently onsite working to repair the damage. This process will take multiple months.

We ask that staff, students, and the public stay out of the work zone for safety reasons during this time. Please stay out of areas that are barricaded or have caution tape up.

Thank you for your patience and cooperation at this time!

shared_text:
Sutherlin FFA Chapter
September 18, 2018 at 7:22 PM ·

Back to justanotherTuesday...

The day ended with 12+ students heading to collect acorns for partnershop project to propagate oak trees for oak savannah restoration with the Friends of Ford's Pond! A great diversity of trees were collected that will hopefully result in hundreds of future saplings - special thanks to Allison and Craig for the help. This is just the start to this multi-year project!

Before then, students in Intro to Ag toured and tried on different CDEs as part of the Great CDE Days, Vet Science modeled macromolecules in the study of how ruminants work, Ag Business prepped and practice some tough interview questions, and work continued on the second greenhouse!

Busy days and great results!
